It’s 𝑻𝒓𝒂𝒏𝒔𝒇𝒐𝒓𝒎𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 𝑻𝒖𝒆𝒔𝒅𝒂𝒚! 
I feel so vulnerable sharing these pics but it’s important to see how far I’ve come in so little time...
🆆🅷🆈?
⠀
Because 2020 has been the year of struggles
 -virtual school, working remotely, a world-wide pandemic, closed and canceled activities, prominent racial injustices...and the list goes on...
⠀
 It feels like 2020 has been an episode from the 𝕋𝕨𝕚𝕝𝕚𝕘𝕙𝕥 ℤ𝕠𝕟𝕖...
⠀
It can often be difficult to find the silver lining in such challenging times.
But here’s an attempt:
⠀
💻Virtual school and working from home means being around my kiddos and reconnecting in a way we couldn’t before
⠀
🌎 A world-wide pandemic means neighbors helping neighbors and community’s valuing one another (even if it is virtually)
⠀
🎟Closed and cancelled events means getting creative and working together in new ways to continue thriving and moving forward...
⠀
👩🏻‍🤝‍👨🏾And confronting prominent racial injustices means an opportunity to speak to and educate my children about loving ALL people, seeing beyond skin color and understanding that God has truly made ALL of us in his image.
⠀
The year of 2020 will most certainly 🅽🅴🆅🅴🆁 be forgotten, but through all of these tragedies, I have seen a strength in myself that had seemingly disappeared long ago. Something good from an otherwise confusing and unprecedented time.
⠀
That’s why sharing with all of you is so 𝗶𝗺𝗽𝗼𝗿𝘁𝗮𝗻𝘁 𝘁𝗼 𝗺𝗲.
I’m sharing strength, determination and hope.
⠀
𝐌𝐲 𝐒𝐢𝐥𝐯𝐞𝐫 𝐋𝐢𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠.
⠀
What’s been your silver lining through all of this?
⠀

node.text: Love you, let’s do some family hood fat stuff together soon.

I’d be rattling my cage if work wasn’t so overwhelming and all encompassing right now and if my husband had some work! But I will rattle my cage for this slice of writing. Thanks for provoking thought! 💓🙏🏻

I remember as a teenager always wondering what we were gonna do. All those curfews on our time and limitations on what we could get into. So many doors were shut to us.
.
On a bad day we’d constantly mumble about how life sucks. On a good day we’d figure out something simple and maybe kinda weird, but it would usually turn out great as long as the company was good.
.
Not having a car would turn into existential conversations on curbsides. Having nowhere to go became chats atop picnic tables in flooded park waters. Having no money turned into laughter over nothing but a McDonalds coke at 4pm. 
.
It was an age of frustration that sometimes broke through to cool. If we’d imagine a little.
.
Adults stink at that. We’re organized and rigid. We can go anywhere or do anything but we leave silly and delight off the agenda. We’re lost without our favorites and specificities.
.
I’ll tell you, I hate all the versions of this lockdown (with lots of words bleeped out). I feel like a freaking 17 yr old again. I’m bored. I’m mad at my authorities. I’m ready to break some rules and sneak out.
.
This sunken teenage depression in me keeps muttering about what sucks and wants to see who else thinks it sucks. I swear I hear a lot of cages shaking collectively.
.
I’ve had a  lot of grumpy days lately, but just like kids with no great plan, we’ve also been stumbling into some imagination lately.
.
We’ve sat on curbs and realized, wait this is kind of silly and fun. We’ve played in landscaping sprinklers. Found new nature. Followed wild bunnies. Run through bubbles in the city. Snuck onto playgrounds. Brought take-out all. over. the. damn. nation.
.
Every time we did something off the wanted-agenda my joy went deeper. Every time we laughed at life my lungs expanded. 
. 
Everything is weird and sucky and I’m tired of being told what to do. But I don’t wanna be lost without my perfect idea of life.
.
I’ve got great company, which is everything. So we’re just going to have to start by pretending we’re just teenagers looking for cool. And go imagine a little. 
.
If it resonates shake your cage💓💓💓

Pagi menjelang. Aku tertidur sedari subuh. Ku lirik jam dinding, ternyata pukul tujuh pagi, buru-buru menuju kamar mandi. Hampir saja tersandung gara-gara kepala masih pusing sebab tiba-tiba bangkit. Aku telah janji pada diri untuk tidak tidur sehabis shalat subuh, namun lalai.

Banyak daftar kegiatan hari ini, masih mengenai urusan semester akhir dan pekerjaan. Yap, pukul sembilan pagi dengan kantuk yang tertahankan, aku berangkat ke tempat kerja. Duduk, diam, mengantuk saja. Sesekali melirik jam dinding, menanti waktu pulang tiba. Ah tiba-tiba jarum jam bergerak sangat lambat.

Dua jam kemudian, sebuah pesan masuk dari staf kampus. Mengisyaratkan bahwa skripsi yang ku simpan di kantor, telah diperiksa dan hendak diambil. Oh ya, satu lagi, aku diminta mencetak persetujuan dosen pembimbing bahwa skripsiku telah disetujui untuk diajukan ke sidang skripsi. Hampir teriak, namun tersadar bahwa aku berpijak bukan di dalam indekos.

Aku pamit, bergegas menuju kampus. Menyelesaikan satu persatu kelengkapan berkas untuk ujian skripsi. Meski skripsi masih banyak coretan, tapi kata dosen pembimbing, ini adalah revisi terakhir, setelah itu, tunggu di sidang skripsi. Menegangkan.
.
.
.
~Noel

node.text:
Jhalak 2.0  Masked Realities. 
In the three months of lockdown, the view through my balcony grill was my connection to the world; capturing the collective pause was my diligent meditation. As the world nervously stirs back to life, with anxieties and stories from the strangest of days, Jhalak returns from temporary retirement. I had put away the series as the new decade rolled in; and rolled in it did - on a tidal wave of epic proportions. What will be the “new normal”? Masked faces now search each other for answers at an aching distance.
Jhalak was my journey to uncover the stories of the city’s heaving multitudes, through a collage of moments that revealed life like a perfectly sliced onion. I found the spirit of this series through the joy in befriending the moment and keeping an eye out for it, like a trusty friend would. After months of isolation, I find myself venturing out again, to look for my good friend, embracing it through the new codes of a new world.
